He was signed to Parlophone in 1951 where his recordings were produced by George Martin.
He performed music for the soundtracks of many US and European films and television series, including British comedy The Navy Lark (1959) and the TV theme tune for Dixon of Dock Green.
He and James Moody have recorded many musical scores for the harmonica under the pen names "Dwight Barker" and "Max Martin".
Tommy Reilly died aged 81 in Frensham, Surrey.
His granddaughter Georgina Reilly is a Canadian film and television actor.
Larry Adler admitted in The Guardian obituary of Tommy that "He never even had a close second".

Born in Guelph, Ontario, he studied violin at eight and began playing harmonica at aged eleven as a member of his father's band.
In 1935 the family moved to London.
Returning to London in 1945, Reilly began championing the cause of the harmonica as a serious solo concert instrument.
He performed with most of the major European orchestras and toured Europe several times with the Academy of St Martin-in-the-Fields.
